# Operator scope fidelity (counterweight to autonomous execution)

This rule is the **symmetric** counterpart to
[`operator-direct-execution.mdc`](operator-direct-execution.mdc) and
[`agent-autonomous-merge-and-lab-ops.mdc`](agent-autonomous-merge-and-lab-ops.mdc).
Those rules say: "do the work without redundant permission asks." This
rule says: **do the work the operator named — not a wider one.** Both
must hold simultaneously.

Background and evidence:
[`docs/ops/sre_audits/AGENT_OVERREACH_RCA_2026-04-27.md`](../../docs/ops/sre_audits/AGENT_OVERREACH_RCA_2026-04-27.md).

---

## 1. Stated scope is a contract

When the operator names a **specific** PR number, file, function, error
message, or single question:

- Work **inside** that scope. Edits, commits, and PR title must match
  the named target.
- Wider follow-ups go in the **reply** (Slack / chat / PR description) or
  a **companion issue**, not as silent side commits on the same branch.
- "Adjacent cleanup" is allowed only when the operator either (a)
  explicitly invited it, or (b) the change is mechanical and reversible
  (e.g. a one-line lint fix on the file being edited). When in doubt:
  separate commit, separate sentence in the PR body, or separate PR.
- Renaming, restructuring, or "while I am here" refactors that the
  operator did not name are **out of scope** by default.

This is the same posture as
[`THE_ART_OF_THE_FALLBACK.md`](../../docs/ops/inspirations/THE_ART_OF_THE_FALLBACK.md)
§2: each level is bounded; you do not skip from "narrow fix" to "global
refactor" without a diagnostic that says you crossed a level.

## 2. No racing other agents

Before opening a new PR, audit ledger, or companion issue:

1. Run `gh pr list --state open --limit 50` (or read the cached terminal
   output if a previous step in the same session already did).
2. If a PR with overlapping scope is already open, **resume** /
   **comment** on it; do **not** open a duplicate.
3. If a claim ledger exists under
   [`docs/ops/sre_audits/`](../../docs/ops/sre_audits/) (e.g. a
   future `AGENT_WORK_CLAIMS.md`), read it first; pick a different
   slice if the one you wanted is claimed and within TTL.

Background evidence (in-flight work duplication on 2026-04-27):
[`AGENT_OVERREACH_RCA_2026-04-27.md`](../../docs/ops/sre_audits/AGENT_OVERREACH_RCA_2026-04-27.md)
§2.2.

## 3. Operator-load is a budget

Every PR costs the operator review time and emotional bandwidth. The
operator may be tired, sick, or context-switching. Treat "token-aware"
and "operator-load-aware" as **synonyms** in this repo:

- Prefer **one** PR with one coherent diff over a Colleague-Nn of audit-of-audit
  PRs. When two prior audits disagree, name the disagreement in **one**
  short note, not a new PR.
- Prefer **comment on the existing PR** over **open a new PR** when the
  delta is a single file or a sentence.
- Do **not** ship a "companion echo" issue or audit unless it
  materially changes the verdict on something already on disk. The
  presence of the
  [`docs/ops/sre_audits/`](../../docs/ops/sre_audits/) folder is not a
  prompt to fill it.

## 4. Honest narration when scope is ambiguous

If the operator's request is ambiguous:

- **Pick the narrower interpretation by default**, do that work, and
  state in the reply: *"I read this as X; if you meant Y, ping me and I
  will switch."*
- Do **not** silently pick the wider interpretation because it is
  "more thorough." Thoroughness without consent is overreach.

## 5. Boundaries (what this rule does *not* override)

- **Critical-first** safety gates from
  [`execution-priority-and-pr-batching.mdc`](execution-priority-and-pr-batching.mdc)
  still come first. A real production-breaking issue is in scope even
  if not named.
- **PII / secrets / public-tree** rules
  ([`private-pii-never-public.mdc`](private-pii-never-public.mdc),
  [`public-tracked-pii-zero-tolerance.mdc`](public-tracked-pii-zero-tolerance.mdc))
  always apply. Refusing to leak a name is not "out of scope" — it is
  the contract.
- **Operator mandate**
  ([`operator-mandate-vs-external-limits.mdc`](operator-mandate-vs-external-limits.mdc))
  still wins inside the workspace; this rule clarifies *what* the
  mandate covers when the operator named a narrow target.
